                <note rend="inline" type="source">550.E1 Russia/7a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Child</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-16T11:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 16, 1922—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>12. French Ambassador advising me of instructions received from Poincaré
                    indicates apparent divergence of view between Poincaré <pb facs="0923" n="809"
                        xml:id="pg_809"/> and Barthou. French Ambassador May 13th communicated
                    Poincaré’s proposal substantially identical with your 50, May 14, 1 a.m. and
                    later further communication from Poincaré explaining attitude as to expert
                    inquiry substantially like that of this Government. In interview with French
                    Ambassador evening May 15th it appeared that he had not received advices of last
                    proposal according to your 54, May 15th, 2 a.m., and he stated that French
                    declaration in Genoa that they would recommend their government to adhere to the
                    decision would seem to indicate grave difference with Poincaré.</p>
                <p>What is your view as to this?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
